Exercice 1

Question

Conduct a prior predictive simulation for the Reedfrog model. By this I mean to simulate the prior distribution of tank survival probabilities \(\alpha_j\). Start by using this prior:

\[ \begin{aligned} \alpha_j \sim \text{Normal}(\bar{\alpha}, \sigma)\\ \bar{\alpha} \sim \text{Normal}(0, 1)\\ \sigma \sim \text{Exponential}(1) \end{aligned} \]

Be sure to transform the \(\alpha_j\) values to the probability scale for plotting and summary. How does increasing the width of the prior on σ change the prior distribution of \(\alpha_j\)? You might try \(\text{Exponential}(10)\) and \(\text{Exponential}(0.1)\) for example.

Answer

The simulation shows that the higher the width the prior \(\sigma\) has, i.e. the lower the rate used in the exponential distribution, the wider the prior for \(\alpha_j\). For the rates from 0 to 1, the distribution is flat enough to cover the almost the whole range of probabilities, from 0 to 1, whereas a rate of 10 has .89 HPDI on the range of 0.15 and 0.85.

n_samples = 2000
a_bar <- rnorm(n_samples, 0, 1)
sigma.1 <- rexp(n_samples, 1)
sigma.0.1 <- rexp(n_samples, .1)
sigma.10 <- rexp(n_samples, 10)

aj.0.1 <- inv_logit(rnorm(n_samples, a_bar, sigma.0.1))
aj.1 <- inv_logit(rnorm(n_samples, a_bar, sigma.1))
aj.10 <- inv_logit(rnorm(n_samples, a_bar, sigma.10))

aj.0.1.hpdi <- HPDI(aj.0.1)
aj.1.hpdi <-   HPDI(aj.1)
aj.10.hpdi <-  HPDI(aj.10)

tibble("σ" = c("Exponential(0.1)", "Exponential(1)", "Exponential(10)"),
       "|0.89" = c(aj.0.1.hpdi[1], aj.1.hpdi[1], aj.10.hpdi[1]),
       "0.89|" = c(aj.0.1.hpdi[2], aj.1.hpdi[2], aj.10.hpdi[2]))

Saving the model for future comparisons

\[ \begin{aligned} Sur_i \sim \text{Binomial}(D_i, p_i)\\ \text{logit}(p_i) = \bar{\alpha} + z_{\alpha,T_i}\sigma_\alpha\\ \bar{\alpha} \sim \text{Normal}(0,1.5)\\ z_{\alpha,j} \sim \text{Normal}(0,1)\\ \sigma_\alpha \sim \text{Exponential}(1) \end{aligned} \]

m1 <- ulam(
    alist(
        Su ~ dbinom(D, p),
        logit(p) <- a_bar + zA[T]*sA,
        zA[T] ~ dnorm(0,1),
        sA ~ dexp(1),
        a_bar ~ dnorm(0,1.5),
        gq> vector[T]:a <<- a_bar + zA*sA
    ),
    data = dat,
    chains = 4,
    cores = 4,
    log_lik = TRUE
)

Question

Revisit the Reedfrog survival data, data(reedfrogs). Start with the varying effects model from the book and lecture. Then modify it to estimate the causal effects of the treatment variables pred and size, including how size might modify the effect of predation. An easy approach is to estimate an effect for each combination of pred and size. Justify your model with a DAG of this experiment.

Modeling

Comparing σ_α

The model presented in the class (m1) had \(\sigma_\alpha\) ranging from 1.35 and 2.00, with mean of 1.64. Adding a coefficient for Predation and Size to the model, resulting in the model m2, lowered this value to the range of 0.14 to 0.54, with mean of 0.75. Finally, by adding a coefficient for Predation and Density, the value lowered slightly to the range of 0.14 to 0.48, with mean of 0.69.

The difference between \(\sigma_\alpha^1\), \(\sigma_\alpha^2\), and \(\sigma_\alpha^3\) is due to the fact that the variables added to the model are causes for the variation of the survival rate. Predation alone has a strong effect, dissolving a good deal of the variation spread across the tanks. Size, on other hand, lowers the variation in the cases where Predation is also seen, lowering the survival rates if predators find big tadpoles. This is the reason for the drop from \(\sigma_\alpha^1\) to \(\sigma_\alpha^2\). Also, as density is a cause for survival (tough small), particularly in presence of predators, its addition in the model causes part of the variation previously spread by the tanks variable to dissolve.
